        .custom-scrollbar::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb { background: #cbd5e1; border-radius: 10px; }
        .custom-scrollbar::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb:hover { background: #94a3b8; }
      `}</style>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;

payload.text:
The word file is loaded in the **`App.tsx`** component within a `useEffect` hook that runs once when the application initializes. 

Specifically, you can find it near the top of the `App` component (around line 95 in the provided code):

```tsx
// Load enable1.txt on init
useEffect(() => {
  if (WORD_CHECKER === 'LOCAL') {
    fetch('./enable1.txt')
      .then(res => res.text())
      .then(text => {
        // Splitting by newline and storing as a Set for O(1) lookup performance
        const words = text.split(/\r?\n/).map(w => w.trim().toUpperCase());
        setWordList(new Set(words));
      })
      .catch(err => console.error("Failed to load local word list:", err));
  }
}, []);
```

### Key Details:
1.  **Conditional Loading**: It only fetches the file if `WORD_CHECKER` is set to `'LOCAL'` in your `config.ts`.
2.  **Performance**: The words are stored in a `Set` object. This ensures that when you type a word, the check happens instantly (O(1) time complexity) regardless of the size of the word list.
3.  **Normalization**: All words are trimmed and converted to uppercase during load to match the user's input style.

